===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|enm}} {{term|seyen|lang=enm}}, {{term|seggen|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang}} {{term|secgan|secġan|to say, speak|lang=ang}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{recons|sagjanan||to say|lang=gem-pro}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{recons|sekʷe-|lang=ine-pro}}, {{recons|skʷē-||to tell, talk|lang=ine-pro}}. Cognate with {{etyl|fy|-}} {{term|sizze||to say|lang=fy}}, {{etyl|nl|-}} {{term|zeggen||to say|lang=nl}}, {{etyl|de|-}} {{term|sagen||to say|lang=de}}, {{etyl|sv|-}} {{term|säga||to say|lang=sv}}.

====Verb====
{{en-verb|says|saying|said}}

# To [[pronounce]].
#: ''Please '''say''' your name slowly and clearly.''
# To [[recite]].
#: ''Martha, will you '''say''' the Pledge of Allegiance?''
# To [[communicate]], either verbally or in writing.
#: ''He '''said''' he would be here tomorrow.''
# To [[indicate]] in a written form.
#: ''The sign '''says''' it’s 50 kilometres to Paris.''
# {{impersonal}} to have a common expression; {{non-gloss definition|used in singular passive voice or plural active voice to indicate a rumor or well-known fact}}.
#: ''They '''say''' "[[when in Rome, do as the Romans do]]", which means "behave as those around you do."''
#* '''1815''', [[w:George Gordon Byron, 6th Baron Byron|George Gordon Byron]], ''[[q:The Hebrew Melodies/They say that Hope is happiness|The Hebrew Melodies/They say that Hope is happiness]]:
#*: They '''say''' that Hope is happiness; But genuine Love must prize the past.
#* '''1819''', Great Britain Court of Chancery, ''Reports of Cases Argued and Determined in the High Court of Chancery'', page 8:
#*: It is '''said''', a bargain cannot be set aside upon inadequacy only.
#* '''1841''', Christopher Marshall, ''The Knickerbocker (New-York Monthly Magazine)'', page 379:
#*: It’s '''said''' that fifteen wagon loads of ready-made clothes for the Virginia troops came to, and stay in, town to-night.
# {{informal|imperative}} Let's say; used to mark an example, supposition or hypothesis.
#* '''1984''', Martin Amis, ''Money: a suicide note‎''
#: ''A holiday somewhere warm – Florida, '''say''' – would be nice.''
#: '''''Say''' he refuses. What do we do then?''
#*: I've followed Selina down the strip, when we're shopping, '''say''', and she strolls on ahead, wearing sawn-off jeans and a wash-withered T-shirt...

